Gwyneth-Martha feud heats up with Gersh hiring

By Keith J. Kelly 



View author archive
email the author
follow on twitter
Get author RSS feed



 


Name(required)



Email(required)



Comment(required)










 

									October 6, 2014 | 2:10pm
												


Modal Trigger






AP / CG Images






More On:
martha stewart

How to live it up in the Hamptons, Martha Stewart-style

Martha Stewart is diving into apparel and skincare

Blame Martha Stewart for Yankees' ruined perfect game

Martha Stewart launches virtual wine store




The rivalry between domestic diva Martha Stewart and Gwyneth Paltrow amped up Monday when the Oscar-winning actress hired Lisa Gersh to be the CEO of Goop, her fledgling lifestyle and e-commerce company.
Gersh is the former chief of Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia, who exited in early 2013 after only a year on the job.
Paltrow, 42, has been using the 6-year-old Goop to move slowly but steadily into Stewart’s sweet spot — that is, handing out advice on home, food and fashion.
In fact, Goop, which Paltrow and Gersh prefer to present with a lowercase “g,” sometimes publishes recipes adapted from Stewart.
Stewart, 73, has been curtly dismissive of Paltrow’s efforts to crack the personal lifestyle multimedia genre that Stewart has pioneered with books, magazines, Web properties and TV shows.
In a recent interview, Stewart said Paltrow should pipe down and stick to acting.
“She just needs to be quiet,” Stewart was quoted as telling Net-A-Porter’s Porter magazine. “She’s a movie star. If she were confident in her acting, she wouldn’t be trying to be Martha Stewart.”
Paltrow started Goop in London but recently moved the company to the US and is clearly intent on expanding what has been a money-losing e-commerce company.
“Lisa is a visionary leader with unparalleled creativity and savvy,” Paltrow said in making the announcement. “She’s the perfect person to build on the momentum we have already created at goop and to diversify our opportunities to bring goop’s positive energy directly to consumers in what they read, what they try and what they buy and how they live.”
Gersh, 55, who worked at NBC before MSLO and co-founded Oxygen Media, hinted that part of her job at Goop would be to bring new products to market. But she did not say if any of those new products would be a magazine.
Moving into print would make Paltrow even more of a rival to Stewart.
“Building on goop’s unique success, we’ll continue to invest in the company, expand globally and launch next product lines and partnerships. The future of commerce is all tied to best in class, trusted, distinctive curated content.”
Goop had 2012 revenues of $1.9 million and posted a loss of $40,000 in that year, according to documents on file with Companies House in Britain, which tracks corporate results.
Paltrow and Goop’s previous CEO, Sebastian Bishop, who left earlier this year, pulled in combined salaries of almost $600,000 in 2012, the last year for which figures are available. The filing for 2013 is overdue, according to Companies House.
With its move to the US, Goop recently incorporated in New York.
Goop also recently engaged in a legal battle with Charles Plotkin, a Hunter College professor and nutritional guru, over its use of the “Diet Detective” phrase that Plotkin claims the company used without permission.
The suit, filed in Manhattan state court, was recently settled, according to Plotkin, who on Monday declined to divulge details.
Goop also contributed about $6,000 to three charities: the Sandy Hook Foundation, the Pencils of Promise and the Edible Schoolyard Project.
